5.how to handle peak traffic after an launch of new product in web app

Ans. To handle peak traffic after launching a new product, I use horizontal auto-scaling, load balancing. 

6.there are multiple micro services and multiple websites, I want to ensure security how do you handle it 

Ans. ( Through Security groups, Web Application firewall, IAM.VPN etc)

7.what is CSI drivers

Ans. (A CSI driver is a Container Storage Interface driver that connects Kubernetes with external storage systems)
Kubernetes uses CSI drivers for cloud storage like AWS EBS, Azure Disk, and GCP PD. CSI standardizes storage and
lets vendors release new features without modifying Kubernetes.”
Kubernetes → Calls CSI driver → Creates disk → Attaches → Mounts to pod.

8.what is helm template and helm install
9.what is helpers files in helm
10.how do you rotate the secrets in key vault and implement .pfx certificate in application gateway , along with ingress/controller in AKS

11.architecture of Kubernetes 

Ans. ( 1 cluster having 1 master node (Kubeapi, kube scheduler, kube controller, etcd) & Child node ( Kubelet, kube proxy, container engine)

12.what is Service principle in azure – provide an example 
13.there is an backend API, I want securely communicate with other, how do you implement it

14.what is daemonset and statefulset 

Ans. (A DaemonSet ensures that one pod runs on every node)
DaemonSet
“DaemonSet runs one pod per node and is used for node-level services like logging and monitoring agents.”

StatefulSet
“StatefulSet manages stateful applications that require persistent storage, stable identity, and ordered deployments, such as databases.”
DaemonSet = 1 per node
StatefulSet = stable pods + stable storage

15.am having an range of ip address 10.0.0.0/16 , I want to have 10.0.0.0/21 subnets , how will I achieve it terraform , how do use locals word and achieve it
16.crashloopbackoff – what are the setps you will follow to troubleshoot further
17.what are the branching strategies and pipeline creation mechanism 
18.what are the files present inside helm chart 19.what is CNI plugin

Ans.
Helm File structure:
mychart/
│── Chart.yaml
│── values.yaml
│── charts/
│── templates/
│     ├── deployment.yaml
│     ├── service.yaml
│     ├── ingress.yaml
│     ├── _helpers.tpl
│     └── NOTES.txt
└── .helmignore

CNI = Container Network Interface

A CNI plugin is a networking component that Kubernetes uses to provide networking capabilities to pods.

Why do we need CNI?

Kubernetes does not provide networking by itself.
It depends on external CNI plugins to:
Assign IP addresses to pods
Manage routing
Implement network policies
Provide cluster networking
